==English==

===Etymology===
Italian ''crescendo'', [[gerund]] of ''[[crescere]]'', to grow, to increase

===Pronunciation===
Syllables: cres·cen·do<br>
IPA: kɹəˈʃɛn.dʊ

===Noun===
{{en-noun-reg}}

# {{music}} An [[instruction]] to play [[gradually]] more [[loudly]], denoted by a long, narrow angle with its [[apex]] on the left.  Abbreviation: cresc. Symbol <
#(''figurative'') A [[gradual]] increase of anything, especially to a [[dramatic]] [[climax]].
#:''Their fighting rose in a fearsome crescendo.''
#(''figurative, non-standard'') The climax of a gradual increase.
#:''Their arguing rose to a fearsome crescendo.''

====Translations====
*Chinese: (''Simplified Chinese'') [[渐强]] / (''Traditional Chinese'') [[漸強]] (jianqiang)
*Hebrew: [[קרשנדו]]
*Japanese: [[クレシェンド]] (kureshendo)
*Korean: [[점강음]] (jeomgangeum)
*Latin: [[crescens]]
*Polish: crescendo
*Russian: [[крещендо]] (kreshshendo)

===Usage note===
*The musical sense indicates that the figurative sense is an increase rather than the climax of the increase.  The use of this word to mean the climax of an increase is non-standard but commonplace.

===Antonym===
*{{music}} [[diminuendo]]
*(''figurative, non-standard'') [[climax]], [[conclusion]]

